13 (4)(A) "Information literacy" means a subdomain of media
14 literacy that ensures an individual is able to recognize when information is
15 needed and locate, evaluate, and effectively utilize the needed information.
16 (B) "Information literacy" includes learning to ask
17 questions regarding whether a source is legitimate and appropriate based on
18 the information that is needed;
19 (5)(A) "Media literacy" means the ability to:
20 (i) Decode media messages, including the systems in
21 which media messages exist;
22 (ii) Assess the influence of media messages on
23 thoughts, feelings, behaviors, perceptions, beliefs, health, and society; and
24 (iii) Use and create media messages to provide
25 information, send a message, or tell a story in a way that is thoughtful,
26 conscientious, safe, and responsible.
27 (B) "Media literacy" includes digital citizenship, digital
28 wellness, information literacy, news literacy, and social media literacy;
29 (6)(A) "News literacy" means a subdomain of media literacy that
30 emphasizes knowledge of journalistic practices and the news media industry.
31 (B) "News literacy" includes the ability to determine the
32 credibility and reliability of news and other information and to recognize
33 the standards of fact-based journalism to know what to trust, share, and act
34 on; and
35 (7) "Social media literacy" means the application of digital
36 citizenship and digital wellness to address physical and mental health
